The Kano State chapter of the opposition Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) has been thrown into leadership uncertainties after its chairmanship seat became vacant and three factions were laying claim to the seat. The faction loyal to former Foreign Affairs minister Ambassador Aminu Wali has insisted that Babangida Lamido  would lead the party while another faction consisting of the late Abubakar Rimi loyalists have paid homage to a former gubernatorial aspirant Bayero Wanda Gano as chairman. But the most powerful faction of Kwankwasiyya under Senator Rabiu Kwankwaso has maintained that the former secretary Wada Sagagi is now chairing the affairs of the party. A candidate for the party chairmanship, Aminu Saad Beli, told our correspondent that the Central Working Committee  of the party in Abuja has agreed to work with all the various groups and had held series of meetings, and would soon to come up with a unified party with no inclination to any group. He said they were in Abuja and had the assurance of the national leadership of the party that a caretaker chairman will be appointed to prepare the state congress. However Uba Magaji Galadima, a party stalwart from the Kwankwasiyya faction said the national Secretariat had accepted the successions in the party which saw Wada Sagagi as chairman and Jamilu Dambatta as secretary. He insisted the leadership is under Senator Rabiu Kwankwaso and it is the legitimate and recognized leadership of the state and challenged the other factions to present themselves in the national headquarters.